<p class="p">Because of the quadratic nature of 
 <xref ref-type="disp-formula" rid="d1" class="xref">Equation 1</xref>, 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M47" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">R</mi>
     <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> intersects the degree-day domain axis at two points. This results in two threshold temperature conditions for tick persistence, one at 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M48" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">2843</mn>
    <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
    <mtext class="mtext">DD</mtext>
    <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and the other at 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M49" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">1795</mn>
    <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
    <mtext class="mtext">DD</mtext>
    <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. We show the spatial distribution only for the 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M50" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">R</mi>
     <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">1</mn>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> values that were reflective of temperature conditions equal to or above 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">
  <math id="M51" class="math">
   <mrow class="mrow">
    <mn class="mn">2843</mn>
    <mtext class="mtext"> </mtext>
    <mtext class="mtext">DD</mtext>
    <mo class="mo">&gt;</mo>
    <mn class="mn">0</mn>
    <mo class="mo">°</mo>
    <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">C</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. Lyme disease risk occurs west of the Rocky Mountains, but here 
 <italic class="italic">B. burgdorferi</italic> is transmitted by a different tick species, 
 <italic class="italic">Ixodes pacificus</italic> (
 <xref rid="c34" ref-type="bibr" class="xref">Ogden et al. 2009</xref>). Thus, we masked out all geographic locations west of the Rocky Mountains.
</p>
